[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Every single day it feels like there\'s a new Claude Code feature, a new tutorial, another thing that you\'re falling behind on. And this is extremely overwhelming if you\'re just getting started, especially if you don\'t come from a technical background. But today I\'m going to help you fix that problem and'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'show you what concepts I would start with if I was starting brand new, completely fresh today. We are going to cover 35 concepts across four different sections, starting with the things you have to know at the beginning and ending'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with super advanced power user type stuff that you don\'t need to know right now, but you should know that they at least exist. And by the end you\'re going to have a clear road map that you can get started with right away and start making some real progress.'

[00:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And the first concept we\'re going to cover is what is the actual difference between the Claude.ai web app, you know, this chat GPT type interface, and Claude Code itself?'

[00:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Well, it\'s relatively simple. These two systems use the same brain. So I have Opus 4.6 running inside of Claude Code, and right here in the chat menu I have Opus 4.6. The difference is when I\'m using Claude Code, this brain has a'

[01:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'body. It has hands. It can actually do things on my behalf, whether that\'s write code, whether that\'s access my emails, whether that\'s to interact with my computer itself. That\'s the biggest difference. Claude Code can actually do'

[01:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'things for me by and large. Now, concept number two is about installing Claude Code, and luckily for us this is relatively simple. If you just Google Claude Code install, it will bring you to the Claude Code documentation. And'

[01:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'all we have to do is copy and paste a single line of code into the terminal, or if you\'re on Windows, something like PowerShell. Now, the one you\'re going to choose is depending on your operating system. So if you\'re using Mac OS,'

[01:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Linux, or WSL, you will just copy this. And if you\'re using Windows PowerShell, you will copy this. To find your terminal or to find PowerShell, you\'re just going to go to the search menu, same thing in Mac. I\'m on Windows. Type in PowerShell. It will give you a scary'

[01:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'interface like this. You\'re just going to paste it, run this command, and then it will run you through the setup wizard. It\'s very simple. It\'s going to ask you to log in, and you will use your actual subscription plan. And after you run through the setup, to actually'

[02:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'launch Cloud Code, you can just type in Cloud. And you will see something like this. But now we move on to concept three, which is where do we actually use Cloud Code? Because there\'s actually a lot of options. Because while I can use Cloud'

[02:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Code in the terminal like this, I can also use the Cloud desktop app as well. This is also Cloud Code. And then we have Code Work Here\'s as well. What about Code Work? And what about chat? Or what about'

[02:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'something like VS Code, an IDE, an integrated development environment, where I do have the terminal up right here, same as this PowerShell situation, but I have the ability to look at my files, and I have another window here,'

[02:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'right? It\'s all very, very confusing. Again, especially if you aren\'t used to any of this. Well, the truth is, it doesn\'t really matter all that much. At the end of the day, the most powerful version is the version that lets you work in the terminal, whether that\'s'

[02:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'using something like VS Code, which I will show you how to do today, or you\'re just using the terminal raw, like in PowerShell or something like that. But when you get started, if that\'s all too much for you, and you\'re like, "Hey, I just want the easy-to-understand'

[03:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'interface inside the Cloud Code desktop app, or even Code Work." For most users, 99% of the things they are going to do can be done in any of these spaces. You\'re not going to be losing out. That'

[03:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'being said, I do implore you to try out the terminal, at least for the beginning. Give it a week or two, and if at the end of that, you know, time period, you\'re still like, "Ah, this is too much. It\'s just not for me." Go ahead and move to these other ones,'

[03:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'whether that\'s Cloud Code or even Code Work. Because you can always go from the terminal to these. It\'s a little harder if you get used to something that kind of has, you know, the bumper rails on it, and then you try to move to something more powerful.'

[03:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And as easy as is for me to say, the terminal isn\'t as scary as it looks because at the end of the day, it\'s just a prompt window. We\'re just going to be prompting Claude code inside of the terminal in the same way that you would'

[04:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'chat GPT on the web app. And like I said, we will use VS Code for today because I think it\'s an easy stepping stone into the terminal environment. This is what is called an IDE, an integrated development environment. It\'s still the terminal, but it\'s just a more'

[04:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'friendly way to view it because you can see over here I have this explorer tab. So when we start working inside of a file, everything I create inside of the file, I can see here and I can actually open up over here and that\'ll be more obvious later in the video. Now using VS'

[04:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Code, Visual Studio Code is totally free. If you search up VS Code in Google and click the first link, you will be brought here, the open source AI code editor. You\'re just going to download it, run through the install wizard, and'

[04:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that\'s kind of all you have to do. From there, just search for VS Code, click on it, and you\'ll be brought to a page like this. You\'re going to go up to file, go to open folder, and then we\'re going to create a new folder today. This folder'

[04:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is where we\'re going to work in just like you would work with any other project on your computer. So I\'m going to go to new folder. I\'m going to call mine 35-test. Click on it. It\'s select folder, and you\'ll see a page like this. Next, I'

[05:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'want you to go up to the top where there\'s the three buttons, hit terminal, go to new terminal, and now our terminal is open right here at the bottom just like it was when we did PowerShell. And now to open Claude, I can just type Claude,'

[05:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and there we go. Claude code is up and running. So let\'s talk about concept number four, which is permissions. So right now, you will notice it should be blank at the bottom, but if I hit shift'

[05:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tab, you will see some options pop up. What do all these things mean? Well, these are the different permissions. These are like almost think of it as security settings for what Claude can and cannot do to your computer, to the files on your computer without your'

[05:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'permission. Now when it is blank, we\'re are the default permission setting. That means it\'s going to ask your permission explicitly to edit files. If I\'m on accept edits on, it will automatically edit files without asking for your permission, so it\'s a little bit'

[05:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'quicker. But, if it\'s going to use any bash commands, that means terminal commands, that means changes to your computer, think downloading a certain dependency or program and installing it, it\'s going to ask for your permission to do so. Then we have plan mode, which'

[06:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we\'ll talk about in a second. Now, there\'s actually a third permission, but to do that you need to open Claude in a specific way. So, if we do {slash} exit, that gets us out of Claude Code. And now, if I do Claude'

[06:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and I do {dash} {dash} dangerously skip permissions, it\'s going to open up Claude normally, but you will see a new setting here called bypass permissions on. That means it can edit files, delete files,'

[06:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'download things, all without my permission. Kind of scary at first, but over time, understand this is where most people end up sitting on because it\'s just quicker. I will say I\'ve never had an issue with'

[06:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Claude Code deleting any files that I didn\'t tell it to, although you know, there\'s always those theoretical stories. In the aggregate though, this will save you so much time once you get comfortable. But, if you\'re not comfortable with that yet, you don\'t want it to go crazy, just keep it on'

[06:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'accept edits on. Now, if you shift tab a couple times, that will bring us to plan mode, which is the last concept we will cover in this core essentials section. So, plan mode means that when I tell Claude Code to do something like, let\'s build a'

[07:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'website, it\'s not just going to go out and do it on its own. It\'s actually going to think about it. It\'s going to come up with a series of steps we need to execute first. And what you will probably see here, it\'s just going to come back with'

[07:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'some questions for us. It\'s essentially prompting us to get a better idea of what we want to build. So, plan mode is the number one way for you to get better outputs from Claude Code because it\'s'

[07:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'going to make sure your prompt doesn\'t suck. The prompt you\'re going to come up with is going to have a number of holes and plan mode lets us kind of fill those in because Claude will ask us questions to do exactly that. So, it\'s asking for a type'

[07:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of website. We\'ll say a landing page. It\'s asking for our stack. If I don\'t know, we\'ll just go with number one. And for our purpose, we\'ll say this is for a personal project.'

[07:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And then we\'ll submit. So, just wanted to take a moment to talk about my Claude Code Masterclass because it is the number one way to go from zero to AI dev, especially if you don\'t come from a technical background. Everything'

[08:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in this course is for the beginner and we focus on real use cases to help you learn how to master this amazing AI tool. I put out new updates every single week and if you want to get it, just'

[08:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'head to chase AI plus. There is a link in the pinned comment. So, now is the perfect time to talk about concept number six, which is your mindset when using Claude Code in the planning phase is a great time to discuss this. Now, right now it\'s asking me a few more'

[08:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'questions about it. And we\'re saying we want to make it about this fake online app called Argus. It\'s a social media intelligence app and it\'s going to create this landing page for us. But when it comes to mindset, you need to'

[08:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'start thinking of Claude Code as a collaborator and it\'s very easy to do so in the planning stage because you have this back and forth. But where people get tripped up is in this back and forth, they\'re going to just do whatever'

[09:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Claude Code says and they\'re not going to ask it questions. In one example of us doing it the wrong way was when it asked us what tech stack did we want to use? We just said, "Hey, we\'re going to use Next.js and Tailwind."'

[09:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Do you know what Next.js and Tailwind is? Probably not if you\'ve never done something like this before. Now, oftentimes Claude Code will give you a recommendation and it\'s your best bet to go with it. But if you really want to learn Claude'

[09:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Code and understand the fundamentals of building with AI, that is when you need to stop and tell Claude Code to explain these concepts to you. And that is how you\'re actually going to learn and not just be a caricature of a vibe coder.'

[09:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Cuz you have to ask yourself, if it\'s this easy to build things, what\'s the difference between you and the guy down the street who I can replace you with? Because he can ask those same questions, too, and just hit accept, accept, accept, build me a landing page. What\'s'

[09:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'going to separate you from the pack and actually build your skills at a foundational level is asking Claude code these questions to explain things to you. It is the infinitely patient tutor, and we need to treat it as such. So,'

[10:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here\'s the plan Claude code came back with for our landing page. And this is what you can expect when you use plan mode. It\'s going to give you a pretty detailed outline of what it\'s planning to do before it actually executes. And you\'ll see some options here. You\'ll see'

[10:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'yes and bypass permissions, which means it\'s going to run what it planned and it\'s not going to ask for permission. Yes, manually approve edits, so it will begin creating things, but it\'s going to ask for your permission every time it wants like create or edit a file, which'

[10:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is very annoying. And then we have this one, no, refine with ultra plan. Now, ultra plan will be in section four when we go into some of the power user stuff, some of these like high-level features inside of Claude code. But for now,'

[10:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we\'re just going to say yes, bypass permissions. And just like that, it\'s going to start building our website for us. And what you see over here on the left are all the files it\'s building. So, this is what\'s nice about VS code, especially when you first get started, all the stuff that\'s being built is'

[10:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'right here. So, it\'s the same as if I actually went into my file explorer, opened up 35-test and looked what was inside. I\'d see the same things. Now, one of the files Claude code created was the claude.md file you see over here on the left. And this is'

[11:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what we\'re going to talk about for concept number seven. So, what is the claude.md file? Well, this is going to be inside of every single Claude code created project. And think of it as the instruction manual, so to speak, for'

[11:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Claude code regarding that particular project. This is something that\'s telling Claude code certain conventions and certain rules you want it to always follow all the time when working inside this particular folder. Now, Claude code'

[11:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'will automatically create this when it\'s building your project. So, you don\'t have to touch this too much. And do understand there are a lot of techniques regarding Claude.md. Some people like me will say less is more. Other people say put as much information here as possible'

[11:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that you think is relevant and you\'re kind of like outside the box rules. All as you need to understand at the beginning is that this exists and whatever you put in here Claude code is going to reference every single time you tell it to do anything. So, it\'s a very'

[11:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'powerful tool, but you want to make sure what you do put in here, if you do edit it, actually is important and it applies to virtually every single prompt. So, Claude code created our web page. It said a dev server is started here on'

[12:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'localhost. Local host is like an internal web page. If you click on this, it will take you to the web page and I\'m inside of Chrome right now, but it\'s not connected to the internet. This is all local. So, this is what it built for us. Extremely ugly. And throughout this'

[12:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'video, I\'ll give you different tips and techniques to actually making this better. But just understand this is where it\'s living right now and we can actually interact with it just like we would a normal web page. But before we get into that, let\'s talk about one of the most important concepts of Claude'

[12:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'code and really large language models in general and that is concept number eight, the context window. So, the context window can be seen if we do forward slash context. And what we see'

[12:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'right here is how much of the context window we have used. In this case, we have used 48,000 tokens out of 1 million tokens. And you\'re probably like Chase, what the heck does that mean? I don\'t even understand what tokens are, let'

[13:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'alone what that really means. 50,000 a million, okay, what what are you talking about? So, tokens are the currency of large language models and Claude code. Every single word is a token. So, every single word here that we\'ve given Claude'

[13:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'code inside a prompt and every word it spit back out at us equals one token. One word, one token. Little bit different in reality, but just let that be your mental model. All the tool calls that uses cost tokens. All the code it generated cost'

[13:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tokens. Everything it does costs tokens. And the context window is our budget. For Claude code, that is 1 million tokens. It differs for each and every AI'

[13:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'system. Now, why do we need to care about this? Well, first of all, if we fill it up, our session kind of ends, and you\'ve probably run into this with chatbots throughout the years where all of a sudden it says, "Hey, I don\'t have enough room. The session is ending."'

[13:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'That occurs when you fill up the entire context window. But what\'s important isn\'t just filling up the context window, it\'s the idea of concept number nine, which is context rot. And that\'s the idea, as I fill up the context'

[14:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'window with more conversations, more tasks for Claude code, the actual effectiveness of Claude code goes down. So, the more I use it, the worse it gets, which means we want to keep an eye'

[14:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of where we\'re at on our context window. Especially since we can reset it at any time. I can pretty much start back at zero whenever I want. Now, this comes at a cost, right? When I\'m using a normal'

[14:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'chatbot, say I\'m inside Claude.ai, and I start a new chat, that\'s kind of painful because everything we\'ve been talking about, I want it to remember. I want it to remember my conversation. I don\'t want to start all over again. That sucks. But if I start all over again,'

[14:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Claude code works better. So, what am I supposed to do? Well, luckily, starting over inside of Claude code isn\'t like starting over inside of a chatbot. It\'s actually much better because Claude code, even if I start all over, and I'

[14:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can start over by simply doing {slash} clear, my session is now reset. Claude code is living inside this folder. It\'s on my computer. It\'s not a chatbot in the cloud. Whenever I talk to it again and'

[15:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ask it questions about my website, it doesn\'t matter that we started a new chat for all intents and purposes, because it can just look inside the codebase. It can look at all these files. It has Claude.md. It has the ability, almost like a human being, to'

[15:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'go inside the folder and see what is what. And therefore, because of that, I always want to be resetting my context window if I can. Because why do I want to be working with'

[15:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a worst Claude code of 500,000 tokens for the sake of keeping a conversation going that I can just have it remember anyways, right? So, there\'s few downside to constantly resetting. On top of that,'

[15:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'as you fill up the context window, your prompts are essentially more expensive. You are using more of your usage because every single prompt is essentially sending everything that came before it. Now, there\'s a caching system, which'

[15:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'kind of alleviates some of that problems, but the point remains, if I\'m down here at token number 800,000, that\'s really costing me more per prompt than if I\'m at token number 50K or 100K. And you see a lot of people complain'

[16:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'about Claude code usage, and this isn\'t the only reason they complain about it, but in large part it\'s because a lot of people don\'t know how to manage their context window properly. So, they\'re using more usage and Claude code isn\'t working very well. So, you can see the importance of A, always having your eye'

[16:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'on the context, and B, always resetting it whenever it makes sense. As a rule of thumb, you don\'t really want to go past 200,000 tokens if you can help it. There are going to be instances where, you'

[16:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'know, hey, I I just need to have a longer window for whatever reason, but if you\'re hitting 20%, you need to ask yourself, do I need to stay in the session? If you don\'t have a very good reason, you need to reset it. And by'

[16:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reset, all you have to do is what you saw here, which is {forward slash} clear. And if there is something in the conversation you want to bring forward, just ask Claude code to have a quick write-up about what you were talking about, and you can copy paste it in the'

[16:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'next session. Now, what you can see here for me, and this is going to be concept number nine, is my status line. So, right here you can see it says 35-test. You can see the actual model I\'m using, and I can see my context window at all'

[17:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'times, which says 2% here, and yours probably doesn\'t say that right now. But you can create that yourself, so you don\'t have to constantly do /context. You can just look right down here and see where you\'re at, which keeps you kind of on top of it. So to do that,'

[17:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you\'re just going to do /status_line, and you\'re going to write a prompt that says something like, "Hey, I want you to create a status line for me that\'s totally persistent, that includes, you know, the folder I\'m in,'

[17:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the model I\'m using, and my current context window usage." Once you do that, it will create that for you, and you\'re just going to have to reset Claude Code, and you\'ll have a status line of your own. So we just hit'

[17:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a ton of concepts right there. Context, context window, the ability to clear, context rot, and the status line. Take those all together, and frankly, you will be well ahead of people who\'ve been using Claude Code for a while, because'

[18:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'people do not adhere to this principle nearly as dogmatically as they should. Now let\'s talk about some other slash commands while we\'re here, and this is our next concept, and that is rewind. So let\'s say you did do /clear. You\'ve been'

[18:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'really on top of making sure that context window is as clean as possible, but you realized, "Oops, I really shouldn\'t have done that. I had something else I wanted to do." Well, if I do /rewind, I can actually go back to previous'

[18:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sessions inside of Claude Code. So I could go back to before I did /clear, and essentially bring that conversation back to where I was, or the conversation where I said, "Hi."'

[18:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This will also include code changes. So if we were talking in Claude Code, and we made some changes to our actual website, and let\'s say I didn\'t like them, I can do /rewind. It\'s an easy way to essentially go back to where you'

[18:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'were, cuz it has these almost auto-save points. Concept number 14 is another one you\'re going to want to know, and that is /model. So /model lets me switch between all the different Claude Code models. So we have Opus 4.6, Sonnet 4.6, Sonnet with a 1'

[19:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'million context, as well as Haiku. So what you\'re going to want to do here kind of just depends on what plan you\'re on. If you\'re on the Pro plan, 20 bucks a month, you\'re probably going to want'

[19:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to stick with Sonic all the time. If you\'re on max 5x, you can get away with Opus a lot, depends how much you\'re actually using it. If you\'re on 20x, you can go crazy with Opus all the time. The model is just going to depend on your'

[19:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'usage. That\'s just kind of what it comes down to. How much money are you paying in Thrawbek? When it comes to Haiku, you probably don\'t need to be using this at all. It is an extremely cheap, damn near free model, and its use cases are very specific and niche. So, unless you know'

[19:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what you\'re doing, you don\'t need to play around with Haiku. And you\'ll also notice some other model-related commands like effort. This is how much thinking Claude Code was doing. It\'s going to default to auto, and again, this is kind of usage-based, because the higher the thinking level, the more tokens, the'

[19:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'more usage. So, just depends on your task. Now, the last core concept I want to talk to you about is Git. So, we talked about rewind, right? The ability to have these sort of built-in'

[20:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'save points with Claude Code. Well, there is another sort of save point, and that is Git. So, Git essentially is another type of save point, but it\'s going to be on your computer, and it\'s pretty much saving your exact spot in'

[20:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'terms of the code you\'ve built. So, I highly suggest you use this whenever possible. Claude Code is very spun up and intelligent when it comes to Git, so you can just say something like let\'s Git commit this.'

[20:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And if I say Git commit, it\'s saving it. This will come in handy later, because when we start using things like GitHub, well, we want to take the whatever save point we have with our code and push it to the cloud'

[20:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'on GitHub. And to do that, you need to have committed the code. So, think of Git commit as a save point. Rewind is great, right? Rewind is great in the in the context of Claude Code, but as we become more mature, and as we like to'

[20:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
