AUDIO: 'settings folder. Now, that sounds kind of complicated if if never done that before, but guess who\'s an expert in these things? That\'s right, Claude Code. Claude Code will literally walk you through it step by step to the to like'

[28:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'where it says, "Click on this link. Go to this page. Copy and paste this." So, Claude Code will do all the heavy lifting for you when it comes to MCPs. That being said, MCPs are kind of falling by the wayside. Even though MCPs'

[29:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'were hyped to the moon over the last year and a half or so, they are starting to be replaced by CLIs. A CLI tool is a command line interface tool. Just like Claude Code lives in the terminal, these'

[29:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'programs also live in the terminal. And because both Claude Code and these programs live in the terminal, they are perfect for one another. Versus MCPs, MCPs have a lot of overhead, which means when you compare an MCP versus a CLI,'

[29:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the MCP tends to be slower and less token efficient. So, for 90% of use cases, if there is a CLI available, you want to use that over the MCP. A great example of this is the Playwright MCP.'

[29:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, Playwright is a tool that, if we connect Claude Code to it, it will do browser automations for us. So, it\'s like Claude Code controlling the browser on on our behalf, logging into websites, testing things. It\'s great. It has a CLI'

[29:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and an MCP. The CLI is way better. It\'s like 90% more token efficient. It\'s easier for Claude Code to use, and it\'s, you know, a perfect case study for this CLI versus MCP dynamic. Now, how do we use CLIs?'

[30:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Well, you know exactly what I\'m going to tell you. There\'s specific commands to use CLIs, or what do we do? We go to Claude Code and we say, "Set up the CLI for me." Now, things like CLIs and MCPs, if you aren\'t on bypass'

[30:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'permissions, right? You didn\'t start Claude Code with, you know, dangerously skip permissions, it\'s going to ask you to do things. It will probably tell you to open up a new terminal window and pasting these commands. If you\'re on bypass permissions on, it won\'t do all'

[30:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this for you. Now, part of that\'s kind of scary, right? Claude Code going in, downloading something on my computer, installing it, and running it, frightening. However, if you\'re using a rather popular CLI, one that\'s'

[30:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'definitely been vetted by the community, you shouldn\'t be too afraid of this. Something like Playwright CLI is a great example. The question then becomes what CLIs should I be using? And the truth is I can\'t tell you what CLIs to use. It\'s entirely use case dependent. Do you need'

[30:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'browser automations? Maybe. Do you need something like Superbase for authentication to set up logins for your website? Maybe. Maybe not. The trap here, and a trap a lot of people get'

[31:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stuck in, is they after hearing about CLIs and MCPs, they go down the rabbit hole and they search up every single CLI they could possibly use, every MCP that might be relevant to them, install all of them and use them like crazy.'

[31:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Less is more when it comes to Cloud Code, at least in my opinion. So, over time, you will become more exposed to some of these CLIs and MCPs and it will become rather obvious when it makes sense for you. If you are just getting'

[31:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'started, I think it\'s enough to know that CLIs and MCPs exist. And more importantly that we can have Cloud Code install and use them for us and even'

[31:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in many cases create skills that help Cloud Code use them. So, if you just know that\'s out there, that\'s enough if you\'re in the beginning of your journey. If you are a bit more experienced, well then it\'s just a matter of using Cloud Code'

[32:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'more and also asking Cloud Code if does an MCP exist for this use case? Does a CLI exist for a use case? Oh, by the way, tell Cloud Code, go use your web search and confirm that\'s the case cuz these things are changing all the time.'

[32:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Every single day there\'s a new CLI coming out. Every single day there\'s a new MCP going out. So, I\'m not going to sit here and give you you know, here\'s the 30 you need to know, although I do have some content that hits on some of these things. Just understand it\'s out there and that Cloud'

[32:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Code can find it, install it and use it for you. These are the kind of like superpowers Cloud Code has. Because what I want to talk about for concept 22 is the idea of few-shot prompting. What is few-shot prompting?'

[32:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Few-shot prompting is the idea that when I prompt Claude Code like with front-end design, I don\'t just give it a prompt, I don\'t just give it a skill. I am in fact going to give it multiple examples of'

[32:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what I want it to do in order to better get the output I desire. And when we talk about something like front-end design, we can do better than just screenshots. We can give it actual code, actual HTML that\'s living under the hood'

[33:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that Claude Code can use to better get us something we\'re shooting for. So, what do I mean by that? Well, you know we originally told our webpage that we were kind of going for an Anthropic color palette {slash} design. Well, for'

[33:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one, I can take screenshots of what I\'m going for. Let\'s add some of these cards. Let\'s get the footer. But, we can look at the actual code. So, if I do control U,'

[33:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what we have here is the HTML. So, if I then copy all of this and bring that into Claude Code, that is in essence a form of few-shot prompting'

[33:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'where I have screenshots plus the code to better guide Claude Code to get what I want. And this is perfect for front-end design. So, I said, "Can we get the front-end to better match the Anthropic aesthetic?" Here is the HTML from their site plus screenshots. I'

[33:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pasted all that HTML, it was 2,000 lines, and then I drag and dropped in the screenshots. Let\'s see how that works. And here\'s what it came back with. And it definitely has much more of an Anthropic vibe in terms of the colors. Now, is it'

[34:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'an exact one-for-one copy? Is there still a bunch of work to be done? Yes. Just like before with the front-end design tool. But, the point is by using stuff like few-shot prompting, you have more control of the output. Anything we'

[34:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can do to get away from just prompt and pray and feel like we have some sort of agency in terms of the output, that\'s huge. And few-shot prompting is one of the best ways to do that. But part of'

[34:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the problem of having Claude Code code things, when we ourselves aren\'t a coder, is that we don\'t actually know if what Claude Code is creating is correct or right. I mean, I can look at the output and judge it based on its final'

[34:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'merits, but is what it created under the hood correct at all? It could be complete gibberish, and for most of us we\'d have no idea. Which brings us to our next concept, which is adversarial prompting and adversarial code review.'

[35:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, adversarial code review just means look at the code and tell me what\'s wrong. Now, when you do this, there\'s a few things we want to keep in mind. First is the idea that AI'

[35:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in general, and Opus and Sonnet is part of this under this umbrella, is they look kindly on the O their own code. Whatever they create, they think it\'s good. So, if I tell, "Hey, look at the'

[35:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'code and tell me what\'s wrong." It might come back with a few things, but by and large, it\'s going to think what it did is correct, and that shouldn\'t really be a surprise. So, if I want to make sure that what I wrote was correct, there\'s'

[35:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'kind of two options. The first is I can create another terminal, and I can start up Claude Code again, so I have Claude Code in two terminals, and I have a different session of Claude Code take a look at the code we created inside of'

[35:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this code base. And I tell it to be adversarial. I tell it to like look at it with a discerning eye. I tell it, "Hey, imagine you\'re some nerd on Reddit who hates AI, and tell me what\'s wrong with this code base." Right? That\'s the first way to do it. The second way is to'

[36:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'use a different AI entirely to do the code review. And a great way to do this is using the Codex plugin for Claude Code. So, OpenAI, aka makers of ChatGPT, makers of Codex, have a plugin for Claude Code. So, if you pay for ChatGPT'

[36:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'subscription, 20 bucks a month, you can use this plugin. In fact, you can actually use it for free as well, but I believe the model is downgraded. But, we can install this just in the same way we install a skill and have Codex review'

[36:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'our code. And they have a specific command for adversarial review. So, if you\'re someone who\'s like, "I just don\'t believe what Opus is saying and I want a second set of eyes that aren\'t also'

[36:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Opus." Well, Codex plugin is perfect. How do you install it? Very simple. Take this URL, paste it into Claude Code and say, "Hey, I want to install Codex plugin." And it will run you through it. And you just would do {forward slash}'

[36:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Codex review or {forward slash} Codex adversarial review. And I think this is really important, especially if you\'re doing something more complicated. You know, we\'re doing something here with a front end like a landing page. There\'s only so much it can screw up, but the'

[37:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'more complex the project, the bigger the project, the more you\'re going to get out of something like an adversarial review. And this is great, especially, especially, especially if you don\'t come from a technical background. You don\'t'

[37:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'know what it built. So, at the very least, you want someone who does know what\'s going on, aka another model, tell you if it was good or not. So, now we\'re in section four, the power'

[37:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'user section. Everything we\'ve talked about up until this point is something you should be striving to master within your first few weeks. If you can get comfortable with everything up until now, you will be well ahead of your average Claude Code user. Everything we'

[37:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'are now about to discuss though, this is more for the power user, for someone who\'s more experienced. You don\'t need to start implementing these things right away, but you do need to know they exist because as you become more experienced, you will eventually hit some walls and'

[37:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'some of the stuff you\'re going to be exposed to here can help you. So, just know they\'re out there, know there\'s possibilities beyond everything that we\'ve termed fundamental or core to Claude Code. And the first two concepts'

[38:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we\'re going to hit are all about custom commands, custom {forward slash} commands. So, when I do {forward slash} as you have realized at this point, is there are a bunch of commands that will prompt Claude Code to do something.'

[38:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Things like clear, right? We talked about that with context raw and starting a new session. But, we can create our own. Often times, they are in the form of a skill. So, you use the custom skill creator to create skills which you'

[38:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'invoke with a forward {slash} command. One of the favorite ones I use is yt-pipeline. This is my YouTube custom skill research workflow. Because skills in Cloud Code'

[38:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'don\'t just have to be simple things like a front-end design text prompt that says, "Hey, when we create a front-end design, make sure you do X, Y, and Z." Custom skills, custom {slash} commands, they can be workflows. They can be'

[38:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'something that tells Cloud Code, "I want you to do A, then I want you to do B, then I want you to do C, I want you to do D." It becomes like its own automation. That\'s what my custom one does, and then it uses sub-skills. So, it\'s a higher-order'

[39:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'skill that calls additional skills below it, and it uses things like CLIs. So, your custom {slash} commands, your custom skills, your custom workflows can be pretty complicated, but they can save you a ton of time. Like I said, this'

[39:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'uses the Notebook LM Pie. It goes on to YouTube. It\'s able to use the Notebook LM actual application through Cloud Code to help me do research. And so, whatever you do that has multiple steps that you'

[39:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'do multiple times a day, you should be turning into a custom {slash} command. Custom commands can also be something like hooks. Hooks inside of Cloud Code tell Cloud Code to do something before a specific command or after a specific'

[39:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'command. These can be huge productivity boosts. My favorite hook is one that plays a noise every time it finishes a command. You probably haven\'t been able to hear it in this video, but anytime'

[40:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Cloud Code finishes a command, I get an audible sound. Now, why would you want that? Well, over time, you\'ll realize, especially when you have multiple terminals up, or it\'s running on a long task and you kind of just forget about'

[40:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it, and you find yourself doom-scrolling in between, it\'s great to have some sort of audible cue to say, "Hey, I\'m done. Let\'s get back to work." I would totally do that if I was you and it\'s very simple to create these things. You just'

[40:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'say, "Create a custom hook or create a hook that plays a noise plays a noise, I can\'t type, when Claude Code finishes a task." That simple. And you could have that'

[40:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'hook be anything. Doesn\'t have to be a noise. It could send you an email for all you wanted every time it completes a task, right? Claude Code is infinitely customizable and custom slash commands and custom hooks are a great way to leverage that. Now, the next concept'

[40:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we\'re going to talk about are all about sub-agents and agent teams. So, when you\'re working inside of Claude Code at any time, it can autonomously, on its own, spawn sub-agents to do tasks on its behalf. Let\'s imagine I was researching'

[41:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'something about Claude Code skills and I wanted to know I wanted to go out to the web and find me information about Claude Code skills. Well, it could spin up a sub-agent that\'s all it\'s doing is web'

[41:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'search. So, Claude Code is essentially creating a second instance of Claude Code, just like you created a second terminal, and it\'s telling that sub-version of Claude Code, "Hey, go search the web for me."'

[41:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It could do that for any number of tasks it wants and sometimes it will create multiple sub-agents to do multiple things all at the same time. You, as the human being, don\'t really interact with these sub-agents and they'

[41:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have a specific task, they complete the task and then they bring the information back to the main Claude Code instance. Now, you have the ability to create sub-agents on your own, but for the most part, Claude Code does this all'

[41:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'automatically when it needs to. You just need to understand how it works theoretically because you\'re kind of wasting your time to create sub-agents on your own. But, this system can have some downsides. Let\'s say I told Claude Code to create a more complicated web page than the one we\'ve been working on.'

[42:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And so, it creates three sub-agents on its own. It creates a sub-agent for front-end design, what we\'ve been doing. It creates another sub-agent for authentication, like a login page, and it creates another sub-agent for payments. Think like'

[42:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Stripe. The issue is these guys don\'t talk to one another. Front-end design doesn\'t talk to authentication. Authentication doesn\'t talk to payments, which can be an issue because we\'re all trying to be on the same sheet of music, yet with these'

[42:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'standard sub-agent, you know, paradigm, they\'re all in a silo. They do their own thing, and they come back to the main Claude code session, and then this guy has to figure it out if everything actually matches up. Well, enter agent'

[42:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'teams. Agent teams is similar in that Claude code will spawn these sub-agents. However, they now talk to one another. So, front-end design can'

[42:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'talk to authentication. Authentication can talk with payments. Payments can talk with front-end design. And oftentimes, it will actually spawn an additional sub-agent whose entire job'

[43:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is to coordinate what these three guys are doing, right? Kind of acting like a middle manager for a team. It\'s trying to mimic a real human team setup, which means your primary Claude code doesn\'t'

[43:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have to coordinate everything on its own. Everything is done at the sub-agent level. This is great. This is a more sophisticated setup than your normal sub-agents. However, it\'s not for free. Because of that coordination that have'

[43:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'all three these guys talk to one another, that costs more tokens. Furthermore, this is an experimental feature. What do I mean by experimental feature? I mean you need to explicitly enable this inside of your'

[43:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'settings.json. How do you do that? Well, you can go to dot Claude and edit yourself, or, and you know what I\'m going to say, copy this page, or copy the URL, go inside of Claude code, and tell Claude code to enable agent teams'

[44:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'on your behalf. Once you do that, to actually use agent teams, you need to explicitly tell Claude code you want to use agent teams. In their example here, they said create an agent team. So, it\'s not going to do it automatically, no'

[44:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'matter how you say it, you have to say create an agent team. So, let\'s see this in action. We\'re going to say create an agent team to work on this webpage. One agent for front-end design, one agent to create a form submission for people who want to join our newsletter, and one'

[44:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'agent to research ideas for blog machine. So, again, you need to be explicit. You can see here the agent team it created. So, it has a front-end designer, shows its task, newsletter dev, task, blog blog researcher, task. And in this main Claude code session,'

[44:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you will get updates as the sub agents complete their tasks. And while they\'re working, let\'s talk about multiple sessions, cuz we talked about this for a second, and this is something you probably see all over the place, which is people with like nine terminals up at'

[44:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'once, all working on the same project. This is something you could do. I can have pretty much as many terminal open as many terminals open as I want to work on Claude code. In a sense, I can mainly'

[45:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'create my own agent teams. I could have one terminal here that\'s working on front-end design, one terminal here that\'s working on the form, etc., etc. When it comes to these multiple'

[45:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sessions, there are some things you need to think about. Mainly, kind of what we talked about with agent teams and sub agents at the beginning, which is like, are we having Claude code all work on the same piece of paper, changing different things at the same time?'

[45:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'If you had three humans at a desk, all working on the same report, and the report was on one notepad, you can see the issues you would run into. On top of that, I will say, from personal experience, you can only have'

[45:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'so many terminals working at the same time before you\'re just doing so much context switching that it feels like you\'re being productive, you\'re giving it a lot of prompts, but are you actually focused on any one particular task? Are you'

[45:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actually moving the needle? Are you actually moving forward in any meaningful way? I would argue after two terminals, maybe three, we\'re kind of just messing around at this point. Like, if you see someone with nine terminals up,'

[46:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this is productivity theater. We\'re We\'re just pretending to do something. We\'re not really working at max capacity. But, if you are going to go the multiple terminal route and you\'re going to work on a ton of things at once, you\'re going to want to deal with that'

[46:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'problem that we talked about. Three people at a desk working on one notepad, that\'s going to have issues. How can we deal with that? Well, one way we can deal with it is Git worktrees. So, Git worktrees attempt to solve that problem. Without worktrees, we have'

[46:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'three people, three agents, three terminals working in the same project. They overwrite their work and we get a conflict. However, with worktrees, instead of having three people at the same desk, everybody has their own desk and their own copy of the files. They do'

[46:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'their work and eventually all the work gets consolidated and guess who makes sure it all adds up when we put it together? Claude Code does. Now, to use worktrees, you\'ll open Claude Code like normal, but you\'re'

[47:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'going to use the worktree flag and then you\'re going to name that worktree. So, something like front-end design. So, it\'d be Claude {dash} {dash} worktree and then name the worktree. And then you would repeat that for all the additional terminals you open. And like you see'

[47:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here, this one is called main, this one is called front-end, this one\'s called tests. You would work on those things in parallel and then at the end you would go back to your primary Claude Code session and say, "Take a look at these'

[47:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'worktrees. Let\'s merge these and make sure it\'s clean." A more advanced concept, especially for Git. So, if you\'re just getting started, don\'t get confused and start using this right away. Now, let\'s talk about another power user concept and that is'

[47:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'frameworks. Things like GSD, get done. Things like B mad. To some extent, things like superpowers. It\'s this idea that there are GitHub repos out there that essentially act as an orchestration'

[47:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'layer around Claude Code and change how Cloud Code works at a somewhat fundamental level. It\'s still Cloud Code, you\'re still in the terminal, but programs like this change how it plans certain things, change the way it'

[48:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'executes, changes the way it records its progress. And the idea is that by using these orchestration layers, they help Cloud Code do something. Most often, it\'s it helps Cloud Code handle complex tasks, complex projects. My take on this'

[48:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is that there\'s a lot of useful things in these orchestration layers, but you need to be somewhat experienced to understand when they make sense. Because, just like with CLIs and just like with MCPs, you can be a kid in the'

[48:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'candy store and you think you need to use every single orchestration layer that is out there for the sake of it, as if you\'re just one orchestration layer away from really mastering Cloud Code. I don\'t think that\'s the case, especially'

[48:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'as time goes on. When GSD first came out, the way it handled things like context rot was pretty brilliant, especially compared to how Cloud Code does it now. Yet, a lot of the cool fundamental things of GSD and other frameworks like'

[48:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it have begun to be seen in the base level Cloud Code. Like, Cloud Code out of the box does a lot of these things now. It\'s constantly being updated, it\'s constantly importing these best practices. That\'s not to say these'

[49:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'frameworks don\'t work, it\'s to say hold off on using them right off the bat. Less is usually more with Cloud Code, and just understand what you\'re actually using. Don\'t use these'

[49:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'frameworks for the sake of them. Let\'s talk about the next concept, which is triggers and scheduled task, which can be kind of a confusing thing. Triggers, that can be a lot of different things. That\'s just when a certain thing'

[49:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'happens, we do another thing, kind of like hooks. And scheduled tasks are when we want Cloud Code to do something on a schedule, even if we aren\'t there. When it comes to scheduled tasks, we have some options, and this also kind of'

[49:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'plays into triggers. And that\'s the idea of loop. So, with the loop command, I can have Claude code do something on an interval, whatever it is I want. Now, there\'s a few caveats. First of all, it\'s session-based, so I have to have'

[50:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this exact terminal open for this to work. Secondly, it has a timer, so max 7 days as of posting this, and they originally came up with 3 days, and now it\'s 7 days. Point being, you\'re somewhat limited because it has to have'

[50:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that terminal open. So, if I shut my computer down, that loop ends. So, something like a loop is great for, let\'s say, you were constantly creating deployments, and you were constantly updating your website, and you wanted to loop that every, you know,'

[50:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '30 minutes check deployment status. So, almost like a mini skill in a sense, but it\'s hyper-focused. But, what if you want to have Claude code do something all the time, even if you aren\'t there?'

[50:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The answer is it kind of depends. So, we talked earlier about the Claude code desktop app. One of the things the Claude code desktop app does pretty well is scheduled tasks. So, if I go over here and hit scheduled, I can create a'

[50:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'new scheduled task, which will run every single time, even if I\'m not there. So, I can do a remote task that will work in the cloud. So, let\'s say, "Hey, every morning at 7:00 a.m., I want'

[51:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you to check my GitHub and do X, Y, or Z." It will do that. It can even do a local task. So, I can have a local task where Claude code searches the web, goes on YouTube, uses the Notebook LM tool, and finds me the top 10 trending YouTube'

[51:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'videos in a niche. It can do that as well. One of the caveats of doing that with a local task is that, again, it\'s not session-based, so the desktop app will create a new Claude code session each'

[51:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'time, kind of like creating a new terminal, but my computer needs to be on. Claude code needs to be open in some capacity. So, understand that. It\'s not exactly a scheduled task, no matter what. But, Claude code does have the'

[51:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ability to create scheduled tasks on Windows. So, I have one that runs a GitHub API and pulls the trending GitHubs for that day every single morning. That has nothing to do with Cloud Code. Windows, my computer, my'

[51:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'machine itself does that, but Cloud Code wrote the script. Now, we just have a few concepts left, and one of them I want to talk about, we alluded to at the beginning, is Ultra Plan. What is Ultra Plan? Well, Ultra Plan is kind of like Plan Mode,'

[52:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but it\'s like a super Plan Mode and it works in the cloud. So, if I do {forward slash} Ultra Plan and say, "Come up with a monetization plan for our app." It\'s going to say, "Hey, do you want to run'

[52:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Ultra Plan?" I\'m going to say, "Yes." And then it\'s going to start a Cloud Code session in the cloud. So, it gives me a link, and you can see Cloud Code, just sort of like the chat app, working here. Now, there\'s a few differences with Ultra Plan. One, it\'s not totally'

[52:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'confirmed, but based on how it works, the assumption is there are multiple agents under the hood on this working on this particular plan. So, it\'s a little more powerful than your standard Cloud Code plan. The second thing you\'ll see'

[52:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is that once it gives it back to us, it\'s a little easier to change it and give it sort of your input. So, here\'s what it came back with an Ultra Plan. One of the differences is that I can just copy anything and I can'

[52:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'leave a comment on that plan. I can even give it an emoji response because that\'s the best way to code. But overall, it gives you a just a nicer interface for it. That\'s the big difference. It\'s the fact that'

[53:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'there\'s probably more powerful agents under the hood, again, not confirmed. It gives you a different, more easy-to-use interface, and it\'s easier, as well, to give feedback on specific parts. If you approve the plan, you just click down'

[53:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here, approve the plan, and it ports it back in the terminal. And then you get the option to implement it within the session, start a new session. Start a new session just clears the conversation, but retains the plan, so we get a brand new context window, or'

[53:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'cancel. This just came out this week, so expect a lot of changes with the Ultra plan. Now, we got two more concepts to cover, and the second-to-last one is remote control. How you can use Cloud Code from your phone. The easiest way is'

[53:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with remote control. There\'s a few other ways, namely channels, but I will tell you for most people, remote control makes the most sense. You just use it from your Cloud mobile app, but you need a session open. So, the idea is I'

[54:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'already have a particular session open. I\'m already working on something inside of Cloud Code, and then I hop on my phone and I use Cloud Code remote. With remote control, it\'s almost like I\'m streaming my terminal. So, it\'s pretty'

[54:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'much I see the exact same thing just on my phone. So, it\'s useful in that sense. And if for whatever reason your computer shuts down or it goes to sleep, if it comes back'

[54:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'up, the session will reconnect on your phone as well. And the last thing I want to talk about is finding new tools for Cloud Code. I alluded to this a little bit when we talked about CLIs and MCPs and looking for them on GitHub via Cloud Code, but'

[54:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
